Took a deep look at seasonality across Presidents' first years, election years, and other years. Across two of the buckets (first years and other years), June numbers are on average lower than May numbers. In fact, only 4 of the last 23 years have seen increases from May to June, and all of them (00, 04, 16, and 20) were election years.

Average change May to June since 1999 is -1-2%, but that's elevated by spikes in 2020 (George Floyd protests) and 2016 (Orlando nightclub shooting). Besides those two cases it has averaged -3%, with a positive change in only 2 years out of 21. We'd need a 1.3% increase or larger to be above 10k, which occurred in 3 of 22 Junes (including 2016 and 2020).

April and May total of 6.734m makes passing 12m unlikely. A 34% or greater y/y growth happened 8 times in the last 12 months but only 6 times in the decade prior. The recent jumps can be strongly corelated to the pandemic and the threat to restrictions under the Biden administration. Prior to that there was a surge in the winter of 2015/16 following the San Bernadino shooting and increased talk of restrictions under the Obama administration. Pre-pandemic baseline would have been 5% and that momentum appears to be waning. That said, I'll still bump it up slightly to 7% with the caveat that an extreme event (large mass shooting) would significantly increase this probability.

There were roughly 12.5M background checks Jan-Mar 2021. There was a similar spike in 2008/9 after a Democrat was elected president (and/or financial crisis?), but started earlier (Nov). If we used 2008/9 as a model, the jump was roughly 50% for two months, then stayed up about 30% for about 4 months. In 2020/21, there was also a 50% (roughly) jump, but in January (preceded by more of a ramp-up too, so not the same shape already), which would imply something like 30% above the 3Mish level for Apr-Jun. 3.5 to 3.9 M per month for 3 months gives 10.5 - 11.7 total. But, given coming out of a pandemic and economic slump rather than going deeper in, increased political polarization, and 12.5 for the prior three months, breaking 12M seems very plausible, if slightly less likely than the 11.6M which is my best guess.

On average, NICS background checks increase by 8% year over year. For 2021, this would mean 42.9 million background checks. April through June averages 21.5% of the year, resulting in 9.2 million background checks for this period in 2021. If we assume that 2021 follows a similar trajectory as 2013, the only year with a similar annual increase in January, background checks would drop to half in June. This would result in a similar forecast of 8 - 9 million. There were also more background checks in January and February 2013 than from April to June 2013. Reasons that there could be more background checks are fear of more gun regulation under Biden [ https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2021/03/03/gun-sales-background-check-legislation-back-congress/6906980002/ ] and a general compounding effect where everyone wants to get a gun because everyone else has one. The drop in background checks in February makes me more confident in my estimates, so I'm going with that.
